<span id="more-9737"></span>



<p><strong>ENCOUNTERING MEAD AT TURN A</strong><br>By general director Yoshiyuki Tomino</p>



<p>The January 2000 issue of <em>Playboy</em> magazine, also known as its &#8220;Millennium Issue&#8221;, featured an article about a futuristic living space by Mr. Syd Mead. The concept behind the design was a &#8220;sophisticated pod&#8221;, where one could find peace and relaxation. The illustrations of the exterior and interior of the spaceship cabin were presented in a youthful and playful manner, just as Mr. Mead&#8217;s &#8220;Land Yacht&#8221; had been presented in <em>Playboy</em> 30 years ago. The &#8220;Land Yacht&#8221; was my first introduction to Mr. Mead, and I quickly fell in love with his work.</p>



<p>I was concerned about the 67 year-old artist, because I thought he had lost his drive and motivation over the years. I was worried that <em>Turn A Gundam</em> might be his last work—it would be a shame for such a wonderful and creative career to end with an anime robot project. Those were my thoughts two years ago. I was happy to see his illustrations again in <em>Playboy</em> magazine, which he did after his work on <em>Turn A</em> had concluded. This might sound like I&#8217;m bragging, but Mr. Mead may have been revitalized by <em>Turn A</em> and is now doing well and working again. Either which way, I was incredibly happy.</p>



<p><em>Turn A</em> was not my first encounter with Mr. Syd Mead. He was commissioned to draw a poster during the <em>Zeta Gundam</em> era, so we became somewhat acquainted back then. I myself had gone through a decline in health after <em>Victory Gundam</em>, so I could relate to the grief of a person struggling with his work while fighting what felt like death. Seeing Mr. Mead&#8217;s work in <em>Playboy</em> again really brought me joy.</p>



